GONORRHEA - AUSTRALIA: (VICTORIA) WOMEN, URBAN POOR, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
****************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Tue 8 Mar 2022 06:20 GMT
Source: Daily mail [edited]
https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-10588693/Expert-baffled-five-fold-increase-sexually-transmitted-disease-women-Melbourne-suburbs.html


An outbreak of a sexually transmitted infection is rapidly spreading through Melbourne's outer suburbs, leaving experts baffled as to the cause. New research from Alfred Health has revealed the areas of Brimbank and Melton in the city's north-west, and Casey in the city's south-east, are showing a surging number of gonorrhea cases.

The study is the 1st of its kind to track the geographical distribution of the STI [sexually transmitted infection] over 10 years and found lower income areas further from Melbourne's CBD [Central Business District] were more susceptible.

'Why this is occurring is the million-dollar question,' Alfred Health epidemiologist and biostatistician Eric Chow told The Age. Historically, gonorrhoea was mostly circulated among men who had sex with other men but the research also shows women are getting infected at an alarming rate.

The infection, also known as 'the clap' is caused by bacteria which colonises the genital region and can be treated by antibiotics. But, if left untreated, it can cause infertility in women. Worryingly, there is also an antibiotic resistant version that has been detected in cases in every Australian state and territory.

Victoria recorded more than 7000 cases last year [2021] but experts say the real number is likely much higher with many cases not showing symptoms and going undetected.

Associate Professor Chow said since 2010, gonorrhoea infections in females had increased more than 5-fold. The number rose from 291 to almost 1600 last year [2021], showing heterosexual gonorrhoea was endemic in Australia.

He said lockdowns had not seemed to slow the spread of the infection, particularly in lower socioeconomic areas. 'It's just gone up exponentially among women in the outer suburbs of Melbourne,' Mr Chow said. 'We really don't know whether it is because of the lack of sexual health literacy and services, or whether it is more risky behaviour in those areas. But definitely the outer suburbs are becoming our greatest area of concern.'

The Alfred Institute has established 3 general practice clinics in the Melbourne suburbs of Hillside, Tarneit, and Clayton to combat the outbreak.

[Byline: Brett Lackey]

