Communicated by:
ProMED

["Melbourne is the capital and most populous city in the Australian state of Victoria and the 2nd most populous city in Australia." (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melbourne). A ProMED map of Australia can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8701917,295.

In May 2021, ProMED posted a news report of an outbreak of syphilis in urban poor women in Melbourne's outer suburbs (Brimbank and Melton to the city's northwest, and Casey, to the city's southeast) that was associated with an increase in cases of congenital and ocular syphilis (see ProMED post Syphilis - Australia: (VI) ocular, women, congenital, urban poor, genotyping, alert 20210518.8367315). In that outbreak, scientists were said to be using genomic sequencing for the 1st time to track syphilis cases.

The May 2021 report attributed the increase in STDs in lower-socio economic communities in Melbourne's outer suburbs in part to barriers in accessing healthcare. A report on the effects that social and economic conditions in these areas of Melbourne have on health care can be found in a report entitled "HealthWest Partnership response to the Senate Committees on Community Affairs: Australia's domestic response to the World Health Organization's (WHO) Commission on Social Determinants of Health report -- Closing the gap within a generation" (https://bit.ly/3yiFwrI).

The current news reports above are now reporting an outbreak of gonorrhea, another sexually transmitted disease (STD), in the same Melbourne outer suburbs of Brimbank, Melton, and Casey as previously reported for syphilis, among women apparently in the same demographic group that was affected by syphilis. A map showing the location of these 3 Melbourne suburbs can be found at https://www.theage.com.au/national/gonorrhoea-epidemic-hits-citys-outer-suburbs-20220302-p5a0vv.html. We are not told if antibiotic resistant strains of gonococci are involved in this outbreak.

In recent ProMED posts, illicit drug use, namely methamphetamine, has been cited as a contributing factor to recent increases in STDs in women in both the United States and Canada (see the "See Also" section below). Illicit drug use is associated with sexual behaviors that increase the risk of acquiring syphilis and other sexually transmitted diseases, including having multiple anonymous sex partners, inconsistent condom use, and exchange of sex for drugs or money.

More information on this outbreak of STDs in Melbourne suburbs would be appreciated from knowledgeable sources. - Mod.ML]
